<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="54">
[[ 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">Hypostomus cochliodon</taxonomicName>
Group ]]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="54">Discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="54">
Delimiting the species of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">Hypostomus cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group is made difficult by the fact that the species vary little in morphometrics or meristics, and the species have a well developed ability to alter color pattern. However, the species can be divided into four groups and from those groups it is possible to distinguish the species. The four groups are the intermediate group (
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4125CE0B-B466-47CA-B90F-CF9073FEE6F8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus hemicochliodon Armbruster 2003:29" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hemicochliodon">H. hemicochliodon</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:3F8E55C1-0EAD-49CA-B887-0D953CC48DA0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus sculpodon Armbruster 2003:49" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sculpodon">H. sculpodon</taxonomicName>
), 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
with a unique color pattern, the odontodeless opercle group (
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C7C2629A-1686-4E4E-9E15-59B1D1162CBE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus ericius Armbruster 2003:25" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ericius">H. ericius</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="levis">H. levis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oculeus">H. oculeus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pyrineusi">H. pyrineusi</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="taphorni">H. taphorni</taxonomicName>
), and an undifferentiated northern group (
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hondae">H. hondae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8E17BFCB-CFC3-4096-8202-76C9E23D3D1F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus pagei Armbruster 2003:39" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pagei">H. pagei</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="plecostomoides">H. plecostomoides</taxonomicName>
). The odontodeless opercle group can be further subdivided into a highly keeled group (
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C7C2629A-1686-4E4E-9E15-59B1D1162CBE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus ericius Armbruster 2003:25" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ericius">H. ericius</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oculeus">H. oculeus</taxonomicName>
) and a weakly to non-keeled group (
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="levis">H. levis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pyrineusi">H. pyrineusi</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="taphorni">H. taphorni</taxonomicName>
). Once in these groups, it is fairly simple to separate the species. Principal components analysis is provided for each of the groups although 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="levis">H. levis</taxonomicName>
is excluded from the analysis because it lacks many of the measurements because of its absence of an adipose fin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="54">
The PCA of the intermediate group showed a 100% separation of the species on principal component 2 (Fig. 10A). PC2 is most strongly and negatively effected by dorsal-anal length and anal-fin width and most strongly and positively effected by anal-fin length and folded dorsal-fin length. A ratio of dorsal-anal length to anal-fin length completely separates the two species from one another: average = 111.1 ± 8.4%, 92.5-132.6% in 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4125CE0B-B466-47CA-B90F-CF9073FEE6F8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus hemicochliodon Armbruster 2003:29" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hemicochliodon">Hypostomus hemicochliodon</taxonomicName>
and average = 79.2 ± 7.6%, 69.6-89.7% in 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:3F8E55C1-0EAD-49CA-B887-0D953CC48DA0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus sculpodon Armbruster 2003:49" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sculpodon">H. sculpodon</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="54">
The PCA of the odontodeless groups showed two trends, a complete or almost complete separation of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="taphorni">H. taphorni</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C7C2629A-1686-4E4E-9E15-59B1D1162CBE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus ericius Armbruster 2003:25" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ericius">H. ericius</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oculeus">H. oculeus</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pyrineusi">H. pyrineusi</taxonomicName>
and a complete separation of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C7C2629A-1686-4E4E-9E15-59B1D1162CBE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus ericius Armbruster 2003:25" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ericius">H. ericius</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oculeus">H. oculeus</taxonomicName>
on a graph of PC2 vs. PC3 (Fig. 10B). PC2 is most strongly and negatively effected by adipose-caudal length and mouth width and most strongly and positively effected by interdorsal length, eye-nare length and orbit length. PC3 is most strongly and negatively effected by base of anal-fin length, anal-fin length, and adipose-spine length and most strongly and positively effected by interdorsal length, adipose-caudal length, and postanal length. Although there is no morphometric evidence suggesting that 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C7C2629A-1686-4E4E-9E15-59B1D1162CBE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus ericius Armbruster 2003:25" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ericius">H. ericius</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oculeus">H. oculeus</taxonomicName>
are distinct from 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pyrineusi">H. pyrineusi</taxonomicName>
there are morphological differences (well-developed keels in 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C7C2629A-1686-4E4E-9E15-59B1D1162CBE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus ericius Armbruster 2003:25" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ericius">H. ericius</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oculeus">H. oculeus</taxonomicName>
vs. no or weak keels in 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pyrineusi">H. pyrineusi</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="55">
The PCA of the northern group showed some general trends separating 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hondae">H. hondae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8E17BFCB-CFC3-4096-8202-76C9E23D3D1F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus pagei Armbruster 2003:39" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pagei">H. pagei</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="plecostomoides">H. plecostomoides</taxonomicName>
and a complete separation of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hondae">H. hondae</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8E17BFCB-CFC3-4096-8202-76C9E23D3D1F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus pagei Armbruster 2003:39" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pagei">H. pagei</taxonomicName>
on PC2 vs. PC3 (Fig. 10C). PC2 is most strongly and negatively effected by eye-nare length and interorbital width and most strongly and positively effected by anal-fin length and interdorsal length. PC3 is most strongly and negatively effected by anal-fin length and folded dorsal-fin length and most strongly and positively effected by adipose-caudal length and interdorsal length.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="55">
For the most part, the species of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">Hypostomus cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group are allopatric (Figs. 8, 11, 17). It is only in the Amazon basin that several species coexist. 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:07C2F0C3-785D-4516-ACF2-A239A9197587" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Panaque" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Panaque Eigenmann &amp; Eigenmann 1889:44" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Panaque</taxonomicName>
, the other wood-eating genus of loricariid catfishes, also reaches its peak of diversity in the Amazon basin (Schaefer &amp; Stewart 1993; Schaefer &amp; Stewart 2002). In the upper 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Marañon">Maranon</normalizedToken>
drainage of Peru, there are at least nine species of wood-eaters: 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C7C2629A-1686-4E4E-9E15-59B1D1162CBE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus ericius Armbruster 2003:25" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ericius">H. ericius</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4125CE0B-B466-47CA-B90F-CF9073FEE6F8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus hemicochliodon Armbruster 2003:29" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hemicochliodon">H. hemicochliodon</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oculeus">H. oculeus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pyrineusi">H. pyrineusi</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Panaque" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="albopunctatus">P. albopunctatus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Panaque" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dentex">P. dentex</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5CDACC22-B4BF-4192-B947-11C8A70BBE98" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Panaque" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Panaque gnomus Schaefer &amp; Stewart 1993:333" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gnomus">P. gnomus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5867DF72-5013-4576-B0F6-EB5E341AC6CB" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Panaque" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Panaque nocturnus Schaefer &amp; Stewart 1993:330" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nocturnus">P. nocturnus</taxonomicName>
, and probably at least one species of the 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Panaque" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigrolineatus">P. nigrolineatus</taxonomicName>
clade (distributions based on this study and Schaefer &amp; Stewart 1993). How these species subdivide the wood-eating niche is unknown, and ecological studies on wood-eating by fishes in the upper 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Marañon">Maranon</normalizedToken>
would represent a very interesting study.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="55">
Weber and Montoya-Burgos (2002) recently described 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A557EE83-EE0E-44C1-A3CB-DABE62D79D62" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus fonchii Weber &amp; Montoya-Burgos 2002:357" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fonchii">Hypostomus fonchii</taxonomicName>
and suggested that the species was derived from the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group. The teeth described for 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A557EE83-EE0E-44C1-A3CB-DABE62D79D62" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus fonchii Weber &amp; Montoya-Burgos 2002:357" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fonchii">H. fonchii</taxonomicName>
are elongate and unicuspid and it is suggested that the unicuspid teeth represent a synapomorphy for 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A557EE83-EE0E-44C1-A3CB-DABE62D79D62" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus fonchii Weber &amp; Montoya-Burgos 2002:357" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fonchii">H. fonchii</taxonomicName>
and the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group. This is problematic in that I have not observed truly unicuspid teeth in any members of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group. In all specimens of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group that I have examined, the medial cusp remains present, but is generally fused with the lateral cusp. The mesial cusp remains visible as a slightly darker, thicker ridge on the medial side of the tooth. I have not examined any specimens of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A557EE83-EE0E-44C1-A3CB-DABE62D79D62" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus fonchii Weber &amp; Montoya-Burgos 2002:357" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fonchii">H. fonchii</taxonomicName>
, and I cannot determine whether or not this is the case with this species. The only truly unicuspid teeth that have been reported for the 
<taxonomicName pageNumber="55" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Hypostominae">Hypostominae</taxonomicName>
are the teeth found in nuptial male 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:253EC2D1-1550-4EC3-9C0A-D6486659393E" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Aphanotorulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Aphanotorulus Isbrücker &amp; Nijssen 1983:105" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Aphanotorulus</taxonomicName>
(Armbruster &amp; Page 1996). I do not consider 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A557EE83-EE0E-44C1-A3CB-DABE62D79D62" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus fonchii Weber &amp; Montoya-Burgos 2002:357" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fonchii">H. fonchii</taxonomicName>
as a member of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group as its body shape is that of a generalized, fast-water dwelling 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:E0BC8DAD-9CD9-4E32-920A-063D33AD0E80" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus Lacépède 1803:144" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hypostomus</taxonomicName>
and not the derived shape of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
. Exact placement of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A557EE83-EE0E-44C1-A3CB-DABE62D79D62" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus fonchii Weber &amp; Montoya-Burgos 2002:357" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fonchii">H. fonchii</taxonomicName>
awaits an analysis of its diet, osteology, and external anatomy for the synapomorphies of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="55">
Recent expeditions into poorly collected regions where no members of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">Hypostomus cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group have been reported from in the past are finding more species of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group. Two undescribed species are now known from the Essequibo and Takutu River drainages of Guyana (pers. obs.) and one species from the Rio Tocantins in Brazil (Reis, pers. comm.). These species and a revised key will be presented in future publications.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="56">Phylogeny</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="56">Character 1: Teeth - 0: elongate (Fig. 1A); 1: intermediate throughout life (Fig. 1B); 2: spoon-shaped at least in adults (Fig. 1C).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="56">Character 2: Maxilla - 0: straight to moderately curved (Fig. 3A); 1: greatly curved, almost forming right angle (Fig. 3B).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="56">Character 3: Odontodes on opercle - 0: 11+ (Fig. 2A); 1: 0-10 (Fig. 2B).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="56">Character 4: Longitudinal ridge formed from bone and slightly enlarged odontodes on pterotic-supracleithrum - 0: present (Fig. 5A); 1: absent (Fig. 5B).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="56">Character 5: Nuptial body odontodes - 0: absent (Fig. 2A); 1: present (Fig. 2B).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="56">Character 6: Notch between the hyomandibula and metapterygoid - 0: present (Fig. 3A); 1: absent (Fig. 3B).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="56">Character 7: Buccal papilla - 0: present (Fig. 4A); 1: absent or extremely small (Fig. 4B).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="56">Character 8: Dentary angle - 0: averaging greater than 90°; 1: averaging less than 80°.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="56">Character 9: Sharp keel odontodes - 0: present; 1: absent.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="56">Character 10: Body shape deep and narrow with the head taller than wide - 0: absent; 1: present.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageNumber="57" pageNumber="56">
Very few morphological characters are useful in elucidating the relationships of the species of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="56" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">Hypostomus cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group. Based on the ten characters found, a phylogeny is produced for the species of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="56" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group (Fig. 23). The single tree found has 12 steps and CI = 1.00. Character state data is in Table 8. No skeletal material is available for 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:3F8E55C1-0EAD-49CA-B887-0D953CC48DA0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus sculpodon Armbruster 2003:49" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="56" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sculpodon">H. sculpodon</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C7C2629A-1686-4E4E-9E15-59B1D1162CBE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus ericius Armbruster 2003:25" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="56" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ericius">H. ericius</taxonomicName>
; however, external evidence does provide information as to the potential relationships of these species with other members of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="56" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group. Considering there are so few characters available for analysis, the phylogeny should be considered tentative.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="57">
Also providing support for the basal position of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4125CE0B-B466-47CA-B90F-CF9073FEE6F8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus hemicochliodon Armbruster 2003:29" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="57" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hemicochliodon">Hypostomus hemicochliodon</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:3F8E55C1-0EAD-49CA-B887-0D953CC48DA0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus sculpodon Armbruster 2003:49" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="57" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sculpodon">H. sculpodon</taxonomicName>
is diet. In all of the specimens of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="57" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group examined, almost the entire intestine is filled with small wood chips suggesting that the fishes consume little other than wood. In 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4125CE0B-B466-47CA-B90F-CF9073FEE6F8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus hemicochliodon Armbruster 2003:29" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="57" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hemicochliodon">H. hemicochliodon</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:3F8E55C1-0EAD-49CA-B887-0D953CC48DA0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus sculpodon Armbruster 2003:49" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="57" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sculpodon">H. sculpodon</taxonomicName>
the intestine mostly contains wood, but other organic matter makes up a major portion of the diet (not greater than 50%). It is apparent that 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4125CE0B-B466-47CA-B90F-CF9073FEE6F8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus hemicochliodon Armbruster 2003:29" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="57" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hemicochliodon">H. hemicochliodon</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:3F8E55C1-0EAD-49CA-B887-0D953CC48DA0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus sculpodon Armbruster 2003:49" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="57" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sculpodon">H. sculpodon</taxonomicName>
are wood eaters but not wood specialists.
</paragraph>
